Taking a principled position against any art except traditional Byzantine iconography. No philosophy, no engaging with anything except crude material reality and prayer. Working the land with basic tools. I have written a 600 page tractate on differences between tool and machine.

Wooden cottage, not in the forest, in a village, my neighbor owns a "John Deere" tractor. The soil of my land is raw and dry. Fossils and oil deep below. House interior is basic furniture, scratched by cat claws. One icon in the corner. Tools sit in a box. All meals well salted.

People have grown too dull to be able to understand the sayings of Church fathers and the Saints of the past, but thankfully God has given rise to new holy men today, like St. Paisios and St. Porphyrios, who have translated the old wisdom with new words fit for our simpler selves

When words change their meaning, old wisdom is seemingly lost behind cryptic sentences, but thankfully the apostolic succession allows us to always have someone to rely on. Saints are to us like one of those scientists who learns to speak monkey language when working with monkeys

Wearing a white shirt, buttoned up to the top, and a vest. My wife has a heavy dress on. Every night we take our clothes off in the dark (I have never seen her naked skin) and make love in bed, before falling asleep. In the morning I wake, with an alarm, to dress before sunrise.

We have a gallon of dark coffee each in the kitchen, with burned toast. A French "chanson" is playing on the radio. We make love again, this time without removing more apparel than needed. I walk out, catching an autobus to the next town, where I work as an encyclopedia salesman.

Haha, on a more serious note I'd suspect no one will find himself in Hell for seeing his wife naked, I think the idea is more so to raise an ideal of "monastic" purity in family life, or maybe also referring to the more "spiritual" aspect of nudity, like in the story of Noah
